additive vs interaction effects of genotypes

An introduction with an easy example

Two genes are additive (no interaction!) if

Two genes are additive if the genotype effect of gene A is the same for all genotypes of gene B. Huh?

The left panel in the image below illustrates this. The x-axis is the three genotypes of the CFTR locus. The y-axis is the thickness (viscosity) of mucus. The colors are the three genotypes of the AQP locus (one of the aquaporins).

  1. Look at the three viscosities for the CFTR +/+ genotype. The viscosity depends on the genotype of the AQP locus AQP +/+ has the most watery mucus (makes sense as 100% of the aquaporins are functional) and the h AQP -/- has the least watery mucus (again, makes sense). The difference in viscosity between the AQP genotypes at the CFTR +/+ genotype are the effects of AQP when CFTR is +/+.
  2. Now look at the three viscosities for the CFTR -/+ genotype. The effects (the difference in viscosity between the three AQP genotypes) are the same at CFTR -/+ as at CFTR +/+. This sameness is reflected in the 3 parallel lines between the values at CFTR -/+ and CFTR +/+
  3. Now look at the three viscosities for the CFTR -/- genotype. The effects (the difference in viscosity between the three AQP genotypes) are the same as at CFTR -/+. This sameness is reflected in the 3 parallel lines between the values at CFTR -/- and CFTR -/+. at CFTR -/+ and CFTR +/+. The effects (the difference in viscosity between the three AQP genotypes) are also the same as at CFTR +/+. This sameness is reflected in the 3 parallel lines between the values at CFTR -/- and CFTR +/+.

Two genes interact (not additive) if

Two genes interact (gene by gene interaction) if the genotype effect of gene A depends on the genotype of B. Huh?

The right panel in the image below illustrates this.

  1. The three viscosities for the CFTR +/+ genotype are as above.
  2. Now look at the three viscosities for the CFTR -/+ genotype. The effects (the difference in viscosity between the three AQP genotypes) are a little bigger than at CFTR +/+. The effects of AQP at CFTR -/+ differ from the effects at CFTR +/+. This difference is reflected in the 3 non-parallel lines between the values at CFTR -/+ and CFTR +/+
  3. The exact logic in item two applies to CFTR -/-, except the differences (the effect of AQP) are even bigger than at CFTR -/+.

Key: I think in class that I said something like this: a gene by gene interaction occurs when the genotype to phenotype mapping at one locus is depends on the genotype at a second locus. This is only correct if we think of this in terms of effect and not absolute phenotypic value. For example, in the left panel, the genotype to phenotype mapping at CFTR +/+ depends on the genotype of AQP. But this doesn not mean there is a CFTR by AQP interaction. For an interaction, we need to compare the effect of gene B at each of the genotypes of gene A. If the genotype effect of gene A is not the same for at least one genotype of gene B, there is an interaction. This is shown in the right panel, where the effects of AQP depend on the genotype of CFTR. This is easily seen in the plot by the non-parallel lines.

A less easy example

  1. Without going into the detail, Ill just say the the effects of CFTR and AQP are additive in the left panel and non-additive (there is a gene by gene interaction) in the right panel. Do not be confused by the kinked color lines(. In the left panel, the three colored lines linking viscosity for CFTR -/- and CFTR -/+ are parallel and the three colored lines linking viscosity for CFTR -/+ and CFTR +/+ are parallel. So the genes are additive and there is no interaction.
  2. But, in the right panel, while the three colored lines linking viscosity for CFTR -/+ and CFTR +/+ are parallel, the three colored lines linking CFTR -/- and CFTR -/+ are not parallel there is a gene by gene (CFTR by AQP) interaction. It doesnt matter that some lines are parallel.
